India's New Hope
The latest election in Cambridge, USA - India may be the most important positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters have decisively rejected the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), which has almost always ruled India since its independence from the UK in 1947.
They may feel happy about this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and the leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, has been ruling from the background since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is just a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
The per capita GDP still hovered around $4,000, less than half of China's.
Newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi had promised during the election to bring about rapid growth in employment and income across India, just as he had done in Gujarat as Chief Minister.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activity expanding and attracting business investment from within and outside India.
One important feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, a feat unprecedented in Indian politics.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will lend Modi a hand in his economic plans.
New Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has rich political experience, having held ministerial positions in the previous Bharatiya Janata Party government.
Jaitley is also known for his strategic vision as a sympathizer of business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as RBI Governor, he demonstrated a desire to reduce India's high double-digit inflation rate and attempted to reform some inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
Stimulating economic growth requires time to implement and produce results.
However, if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities provided by these institutions, as primary and secondary education in India are lagging behind.
Only 60% of Indian adults have basic literacy skills.
Teachers themselves have inadequate education, lack of work motivation, and many teachers even fail to appear at the schools they are assigned to.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports shows that private enterprises can also make a contribution in this field.
Fiscal integration.
Large-scale budget deficits absorb national savings, which could have been used to expand business investment. The budget deficit leads to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future tax revenues.
Privatization.
The government's manufacturing and other industrial enterprises operate inefficiently, often consuming national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps to accelerate economic growth.
Abolish subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are difficult to cancel politically, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, with the notable introduction of a fingerprint-based cash transfer new system, India's cash transfer payment efficiency is relatively high.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
As a result, a large quantity of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and regional zoning.
You can see the negative impact of regional zoning on urban land use, hindering development, if you have ever visited Mumbai or other major Indian cities.
Unclear property rights, particularly for agricultural land, have hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign companies are unable to become the majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex national and state sales tax system has distorted domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and implementing a dual tax system has been ongoing for a long time, and it is now time to move into the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption scandals have eroded economic confidence and hindered official decision-making.
India is also plagued by small-scale corruption, with bribery becoming a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and limit small-scale corruption through new cash transfer payment systems.
Driven by strong growth and increasing profit expectations, the Indian stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
